WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.370 --> 00:00:04.981
Hello, I am Kim Jeong Ah, a nurse practitioner
working at Eminent

2
00:00:04.981 --> 00:00:05.750
Hospice Care.

3
00:00:05.750 --> 00:00:11.190
Today, I will talk about the services provided by
hospice.

4
00:00:11.190 --> 00:00:18.279
Hospice is a service provided by Medicare according
to the Medicare Hospice

5
00:00:18.279 --> 00:00:18.870
Benefit.

6
00:00:18.870 --> 00:00:22.546
On screen: Medicare Hospice Benefit information.
Please go to the address on

7
00:00:22.546 --> 00:00:25.610
the screen to see the most accurate and detailed
information.

8
00:00:25.610 --> 00:00:30.190
I will talk only about the most general situations
among them.

9
00:00:30.190 --> 00:00:36.160
If you do not have Medicare, you can apply for
hospice through

10
00:00:36.160 --> 00:00:38.150
Medi-Cal or private insurance.

11
00:00:38.150 --> 00:00:46.104
Benefits differ a little by insurance, so you need
to check your

12
00:00:46.104 --> 00:00:47.430
insurance benefits.

13
00:00:47.430 --> 00:00:51.890
In general, every insurance follows the Medicare
Hospice Benefit guidelines.

14
00:00:51.890 --> 00:00:57.218
On screen: Medicare Hospice Core Services. First, I
will talk about Medicare

15
00:00:57.218 --> 00:00:58.550
hospice core services.

16
00:00:58.550 --> 00:01:06.530
Hospice care core services are the services Medicare
requires hospice to provide.

17
00:01:06.530 --> 00:01:13.730
They are doctor, nurse, social worker, spiritual
counselor, and chaplain services.

18
00:01:13.730 --> 00:01:19.090
So each patient must be cared for by these four
staff members.

19
00:01:19.090 --> 00:01:26.601
The remaining visiting staff are optional services a
hospice company may provide

20
00:01:26.601 --> 00:01:29.730
depending on the patient's needs.

21
00:01:29.730 --> 00:01:33.490
On screen: Medical doctor. First, I will talk about
physicians.

22
00:01:33.490 --> 00:01:39.746
A hospice patient has two doctors: the patient's
original attending physician and

23
00:01:39.746 --> 00:01:41.310
the hospice physician.

24
00:01:41.310 --> 00:01:46.986
So all medications and treatments provided to a
hospice patient are ordered

25
00:01:46.986 --> 00:01:50.770
by the attending physician or the hospice doctor.

26
00:01:50.770 --> 00:01:55.668
When a patient starts hospice, in many cases the
original attending physician

27
00:01:55.668 --> 00:01:59.750
steps back and lets the hospice physician see the
patient.

28
00:01:59.750 --> 00:02:04.540
Depending on the attending physician's opinion, or
at the patient's or family's

29
00:02:04.540 --> 00:02:08.930
request, the original attending physician can
continue caring for the patient.

30
00:02:08.930 --> 00:02:14.197
The doctor receives reports from the nurse about the
patient's current symptoms

31
00:02:14.197 --> 00:02:16.830
and orders medications and treatment methods.

32
00:02:16.830 --> 00:02:21.790
After death, the doctor is involved in writing the
death certificate.

33
00:02:21.790 --> 00:02:27.130
At the six-month point, a doctor or nurse
practitioner usually visits in

34
00:02:27.130 --> 00:02:28.910
person or by phone

35
00:02:28.910 --> 00:02:34.241
to decide whether it is appropriate for the patient
to continue receiving

36
00:02:34.241 --> 00:02:35.130
hospice services.

37
00:02:35.130 --> 00:02:40.390
On screen: Nurse, RN or LVN service. Next is the
nurse service.

38
00:02:40.390 --> 00:02:43.558
Depending on the patient's condition, nurses visit
once or twice a week,

39
00:02:43.558 --> 00:02:45.670
or whenever the patient urgently needs a visit.

40
00:02:45.670 --> 00:02:49.930
They check whether the patient's current symptoms
are being managed well.

41
00:02:49.930 --> 00:02:54.110
An RN is required to visit at least once every two
weeks.

42
00:02:54.110 --> 00:02:59.264
The nurse monitors the patient's symptoms and
continuously follows whether the current

43
00:02:59.264 --> 00:03:03.130
nursing and treatment plans are managing those
symptoms well.

44
00:03:03.130 --> 00:03:07.770
If needed, the nurse educates caregivers, reports to
the doctor, and helps

45
00:03:07.770 --> 00:03:11.250
stop medications or adjust medications that should
be added.

46
00:03:11.250 --> 00:03:17.550
The nurse also refills the patient's current
medications, supplies, or medical equipment

47
00:03:17.550 --> 00:03:21.330
and helps provide additional items the patient
needs.

48
00:03:21.330 --> 00:03:26.640
One question families often ask is, 'How long does
the nurse stay

49
00:03:26.640 --> 00:03:28.410
when the nurse comes?'

50
00:03:28.410 --> 00:03:32.863
On the nurse's first visit, the nurse looks at every
part of

51
00:03:32.863 --> 00:03:35.090
the patient and reviews the medications.

52
00:03:35.090 --> 00:03:38.412
Because the nurse must understand many things,
including the caregiving family's environment,

53
00:03:38.412 --> 00:03:40.350
the first visit takes a long time.

54
00:03:40.350 --> 00:03:46.005
After the first visit, you can think of most regular
visits as

55
00:03:46.005 --> 00:03:47.890
taking around thirty minutes.

56
00:03:47.890 --> 00:03:51.158
If there are many things that need to be done for
the

57
00:03:51.158 --> 00:03:51.430
patient,

58
00:03:51.430 --> 00:03:57.094
in other words, if the patient has many
uncomfortable symptoms, the visit

59
00:03:57.094 --> 00:03:58.510
can take longer.

60
00:03:58.510 --> 00:04:04.270
I would like to briefly give examples of common
symptoms hospice patients

61
00:04:04.270 --> 00:04:05.230
often experience.

62
00:04:05.230 --> 00:04:11.534
They include pain, constipation, nausea, vomiting,
poor appetite, shortness of breath, infection,

63
00:04:11.534 --> 00:04:13.110
and pressure sores.

64
00:04:13.110 --> 00:04:16.470
One of the many reasons Korean patients receive
hospice

65
00:04:16.470 --> 00:04:18.210
is dementia.

66
00:04:18.210 --> 00:04:22.270
Some dementia patients do not have these symptoms,

67
00:04:22.270 --> 00:04:24.690
and some may have only one or two of them.

68
00:04:24.690 --> 00:04:29.070
Or, depending on a specific disease, certain
symptoms may become worse.

69
00:04:29.070 --> 00:04:36.570
For cancer patients, all of the symptoms listed
above may appear.

70
00:04:36.570 --> 00:04:42.050
All the symptoms I mentioned above are symptoms
hospice helps manage.

71
00:04:42.050 --> 00:04:47.923
So if you meet an experienced nurse, or meet a good
hospice,

72
00:04:47.923 --> 00:04:50.370
you can receive better care.

73
00:04:50.370 --> 00:04:54.510
They can quickly catch what the patient needs,

74
00:04:54.510 --> 00:05:00.510
and among nurses, there are nurses who truly care
for patients with

75
00:05:00.510 --> 00:05:02.010
attention and love.

76
00:05:02.010 --> 00:05:05.770
Regardless of knowledge alone, there are nurses who
want to do anything

77
00:05:05.770 --> 00:05:07.650
more when a patient is suffering.

78
00:05:07.650 --> 00:05:12.764
Then, in the process of trying to resolve the
symptoms the patient

79
00:05:12.764 --> 00:05:13.190
has,

80
00:05:13.190 --> 00:05:20.330
they find methods, and I have often seen good
results.

81
00:05:20.330 --> 00:05:26.090
For one extreme example, there was a patient with
colon cancer.

82
00:05:26.090 --> 00:05:31.786
When that patient started hospice, the patient had
pain, poor appetite, nausea,

83
00:05:31.786 --> 00:05:33.210
vomiting, and constipation.

84
00:05:33.210 --> 00:05:38.953
At first, we adjusted constipation medication step
by step, and the constipation

85
00:05:38.953 --> 00:05:39.910
was relieved.

86
00:05:39.910 --> 00:05:42.810
Only the constipation was relieved,

87
00:05:42.810 --> 00:05:46.810
but the other symptoms also improved dramatically.

88
00:05:46.810 --> 00:05:50.870
The patient became much more comfortable than when
first admitted

89
00:05:50.870 --> 00:05:54.170
and later passed peacefully at the end of life.

90
00:05:54.170 --> 00:06:00.187
In fact, not only colon cancer patients, but many
hospice patients suffer

91
00:06:00.187 --> 00:06:01.190
from constipation.

92
00:06:01.190 --> 00:06:06.330
Older patients eat less and cannot drink water well.

93
00:06:06.330 --> 00:06:07.570
They are often lying down.

94
00:06:07.570 --> 00:06:12.890
When they take this medicine and that medicine,
especially narcotic pain medication,

95
00:06:12.890 --> 00:06:15.390
constipation often occurs.

96
00:06:15.390 --> 00:06:17.890
So I tell our nurses,

97
00:06:17.890 --> 00:06:20.941
during patient visits, even if it is difficult,
always check whether stool

98
00:06:20.941 --> 00:06:21.450
is impacted

99
00:06:21.450 --> 00:06:25.940
by inserting a finger into the anus and confirming
it.

100
00:06:25.940 --> 00:06:28.120
If constipation symptoms improve,

101
00:06:28.120 --> 00:06:32.260
many other symptoms are also likely to improve.

102
00:06:32.260 --> 00:06:35.915
On screen: Social worker service. Now I will talk
about the social

103
00:06:35.915 --> 00:06:36.220
worker.

104
00:06:36.220 --> 00:06:37.840
The social worker provides emotional support

105
00:06:37.840 --> 00:06:43.960
and provides and discusses information about social
welfare services such as Medicare

106
00:06:43.960 --> 00:06:44.980
and Medi-Cal.

107
00:06:44.980 --> 00:06:48.120
For example, in California,

108
00:06:48.120 --> 00:06:53.340
they help with applications for Medi-Cal, body
donation, IHSS,

109
00:06:53.340 --> 00:06:57.260
free meal services, and similar services.

110
00:06:57.260 --> 00:06:59.061
On screen: Spiritual counselor or chaplain service.

111
00:06:59.061 --> 00:07:01.120
Next I will talk about the spiritual counselor.

112
00:07:01.120 --> 00:07:04.315
This is called a spiritual counselor, and it is
usually handled by

113
00:07:04.315 --> 00:07:05.380
a pastor or chaplain.

114
00:07:05.380 --> 00:07:09.200
They visit once a month, or visit regularly,

115
00:07:09.200 --> 00:07:13.649
and counsel and care for the spiritual difficulties
patients and families are

116
00:07:13.649 --> 00:07:14.020
experiencing.

117
00:07:14.020 --> 00:07:16.760
Many families like our pastor,

118
00:07:16.760 --> 00:07:21.544
so sometimes they ask us to send the pastor more
often instead

119
00:07:21.544 --> 00:07:22.740
of the nurse.

120
00:07:22.740 --> 00:07:25.240
Bereavement care service for families after death

121
00:07:25.240 --> 00:07:29.860
is also handled by the spiritual counselor.

122
00:07:29.860 --> 00:07:31.000
After the patient's death,

123
00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:33.674
the spiritual counselor cares for and comforts the
grief experienced by the

124
00:07:33.674 --> 00:07:34.120
bereaved family,

125
00:07:34.120 --> 00:07:39.060
and helps support them through a difficult time.

126
00:07:39.060 --> 00:07:44.490
We also provide a service that sends letters for one
year.

127
00:07:44.490 --> 00:07:46.570
The four services I have discussed so far

128
00:07:46.570 --> 00:07:50.570
are the hospice core services set by Medicare.

129
00:07:50.570 --> 00:07:56.090
On screen: Optional services. Next, examples of
other optional services are the

130
00:07:56.090 --> 00:07:57.930
bath aide and volunteer.

131
00:07:57.930 --> 00:08:03.690
A bath aide usually visits once or twice a week and
provides

132
00:08:03.690 --> 00:08:04.650
bathing services.

133
00:08:04.650 --> 00:08:08.810
For volunteers, if a family wants it, we can send
someone once

134
00:08:08.810 --> 00:08:11.930
or twice a week for one or two hours.

135
00:08:11.930 --> 00:08:21.813
They keep lonely patients company or help tired
family caregivers take a

136
00:08:21.813 --> 00:08:23.460
short rest.

137
00:08:23.460 --> 00:08:29.580
Next are additional services hospice provides that
are not care-staff visits.

138
00:08:29.580 --> 00:08:33.020
On screen: Medications and medical equipment.
Hospice provides medications and medical equipment.

139
00:08:33.020 --> 00:08:37.912
Hospice provides the medications patients need and
the treatment supplies needed for

140
00:08:37.912 --> 00:08:38.320
care.

141
00:08:38.320 --> 00:08:44.000
For example, for pressure-sore treatment, hospice
provides gauze, saline, and ointment.

142
00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:51.384
For patients who toilet in bed, hospice provides
incontinence supplies, diapers, chux,

143
00:08:51.384 --> 00:08:54.460
wipes, gloves, and similar items.

144
00:08:54.460 --> 00:09:01.012
For patients who cannot eat well, hospice provides
Ensure or Glucerna to

145
00:09:01.012 --> 00:09:02.650
help supplement nutrition.

146
00:09:02.650 --> 00:09:07.607
On screen: Medical equipment service. Next is
medical equipment, sent so the

147
00:09:07.607 --> 00:09:12.564
patient can be comfortable and the family can care
for the patient

148
00:09:12.564 --> 00:09:13.390
more easily.

149
00:09:13.390 --> 00:09:19.390
Hospital beds, overbed tables, air-pressure
mattresses, wheelchairs, walkers, oxygen supplies, suction machines,

150
00:09:19.390 --> 00:09:25.390
nebulizers, and other items are sent through the
hospice rental company according

151
00:09:25.390 --> 00:09:27.390
to the patient's needs.

152
00:09:27.390 --> 00:09:34.368
Usually, without hospice, receiving medical
equipment requires a doctor's signature, paperwork, and

153
00:09:34.368 --> 00:09:41.347
other complicated steps, but hospice patients can
receive items simply without that

154
00:09:41.347 --> 00:09:42.510
complicated process.

155
00:09:42.510 --> 00:09:46.544
A hospital bed is especially helpful to the patient,
and it is

156
00:09:46.544 --> 00:09:49.570
also helpful to the family caring for the patient.

157
00:09:49.570 --> 00:09:56.101
Sometimes people dislike hospital beds, but hospital
beds can be adjusted up

158
00:09:56.101 --> 00:09:57.190
and down.

159
00:09:57.190 --> 00:10:04.352
Because the head can be raised, we recommend a
hospital bed when

160
00:10:04.352 --> 00:10:11.513
patients have shortness of breath, poor digestion,
or need to eat in

161
00:10:11.513 --> 00:10:12.110
bed.

162
00:10:12.110 --> 00:10:16.622
On screen: Hospice on-call service. Finally, I want
to talk about the

163
00:10:16.622 --> 00:10:17.750
hospice on-call service.

164
00:10:17.750 --> 00:10:22.982
It is called emergency triage service; in Korean, it
is a standby

165
00:10:22.982 --> 00:10:24.290
or waiting service.

166
00:10:24.290 --> 00:10:30.558
Hospice is called a 24/7 service, meaning someone is
waiting and answering

167
00:10:30.558 --> 00:10:33.170
calls twenty-four hours a day.

168
00:10:33.170 --> 00:10:39.710
At our company, office hours are from nine to five,
and after

169
00:10:39.710 --> 00:10:44.070
that Arin answers calls and explains emergency
measures.

170
00:10:44.070 --> 00:10:48.378
When we receive a call from family or facility staff
about an

171
00:10:48.378 --> 00:10:51.250
emergency, we instruct them on how to respond.

172
00:10:51.250 --> 00:10:58.950
Hospice patients often already have medications or
equipment prepared for emergency situations.

173
00:10:58.950 --> 00:11:03.704
If the situation cannot be handled by phone, a
hospice staff member

174
00:11:03.704 --> 00:11:07.270
visits the patient directly and provides the needed
care.

175
00:11:07.270 --> 00:11:12.597
Even when it is not an emergency, families can call
to ask

176
00:11:12.597 --> 00:11:15.260
about medication refills or care questions.

177
00:11:15.260 --> 00:11:21.371
Personally, this twenty-four-hour on-call standby
service is one of the hardest parts

178
00:11:21.371 --> 00:11:27.482
of being a hospice nurse, but it is truly useful for
patients

179
00:11:27.482 --> 00:11:28.500
and families.

180
00:11:28.500 --> 00:11:31.214
That is because an emergency can happen to the
patient at any

181
00:11:31.214 --> 00:11:31.440
time.

182
00:11:31.440 --> 00:11:36.643
A patient may pass away at ten at night or three in

183
00:11:36.643 --> 00:11:41.846
the morning, and we visit, pronounce death, and take
the necessary POLST-death

184
00:11:41.846 --> 00:11:42.280
steps.

185
00:11:42.280 --> 00:11:46.554
Because most families are experiencing a death for
the first time, simply

186
00:11:46.554 --> 00:11:49.760
having hospice staff with them after death helps
greatly.

187
00:11:49.760 --> 00:11:55.848
The family feels reassured, the death and later
procedures are completed smoothly,

188
00:11:55.848 --> 00:11:59.400
and they become satisfied with hospice service.

189
00:11:59.400 --> 00:12:05.058
In our hospice, many patients are in nursing homes
or care facilities,

190
00:12:05.058 --> 00:12:10.717
and we often hear that people like that our company
answers the

191
00:12:10.717 --> 00:12:11.660
phone well.

192
00:12:11.660 --> 00:12:17.140
Many hospice companies use an answering service
company.

193
00:12:17.140 --> 00:12:22.856
Then, after office hours, when a patient or family
calls the hospice

194
00:12:22.856 --> 00:12:27.620
company, the answering service company receives the
call and message.

195
00:12:27.620 --> 00:12:33.767
When that message is passed to hospice on-call, the
on-call hospice nurse

196
00:12:33.767 --> 00:12:36.840
judges the situation and calls back.

197
00:12:36.840 --> 00:12:42.690
Korean patients and families often struggle because
they must leave a message

198
00:12:42.690 --> 00:12:48.540
in English and wait for the call back during an
urgent situation.

199
00:12:48.540 --> 00:12:53.515
At our company, Arin, who speaks English and Korean,
answers the phone,

200
00:12:53.515 --> 00:12:58.491
so communication is convenient and fast, and patient
and family satisfaction is

201
00:12:58.491 --> 00:12:59.320
very high.

202
00:12:59.320 --> 00:13:02.940
Thank you, everyone, for watching this video.

203
00:13:02.940 --> 00:13:07.760
What I talked about today is the general case.

204
00:13:07.760 --> 00:13:12.591
Depending on the patient's and family's situation,
and depending on where the

205
00:13:12.591 --> 00:13:17.020
patient is staying, the services provided may vary
little by little.

206
00:13:17.020 --> 00:13:23.195
Those watching this video may be family members
directly caring for a

207
00:13:23.195 --> 00:13:28.340
hospice patient, or nurses and medical professionals
interested in hospice.

208
00:13:28.340 --> 00:13:32.780
Hospice is holistic care, whole-person nursing.

209
00:13:32.780 --> 00:13:39.688
It provides care not only for the patient's
symptoms, but also for

210
00:13:39.688 --> 00:13:46.020
the physical, mental, spiritual, and surrounding
environment, together with the family.

211
00:13:46.020 --> 00:13:50.612
We believe we are doing precious work by protecting
the final moments

212
00:13:50.612 --> 00:13:51.760
of one life.

213
00:13:51.760 --> 00:13:54.600
Thank you for your hard work in 2024.

214
00:13:54.600 --> 00:13:56.880
Happy New Year in 2025.

215
00:13:56.880 --> 00:13:57.060
Thank you.
